One common issue in those cases is a permission error. To allow AWS Lambda to PutObject in S3, you need to set such permissions in the Lambda Execution Role.

Here is an example of a policy that will allow Lambda to do anything in S3:

    {
        &quot;Version&quot;: &quot;2012-10-17&quot;,
        &quot;Statement&quot;: [
    {
                &quot;Effect&quot;: &quot;Allow&quot;,
                &quot;Action&quot;: [
                    &quot;s3:ListAllMyBuckets&quot;,
                    &quot;s3:GetBucketLocation&quot;
                ],
                &quot;Resource&quot;: &quot;*&quot;
            },
            {
                &quot;Effect&quot;: &quot;Allow&quot;,
                &quot;Action&quot;: &quot;s3:*&quot;,
                &quot;Resource&quot;: [
                    &quot;arn:aws:s3:::ExampleBucketName&quot;,
                    &quot;arn:aws:s3:::ExampleBucketName/*&quot;
                ]
            }
        ]
    }

For security purposes, it is important to restrict the action to only the ones you actually need, such as PutObject, and you can get more information on [this link][1].


  [1]: https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/security/writing-iam-policies-how-to-grant-access-to-an-amazon-s3-bucket/

